#PGML

BEGIN_PGML

Two planes are flying at cruising altitude and happen to come in close proximity. You are in plane [`\textrm{B}`] with a window seat such that you have a nice view of plane [`\textrm{A}`].
Plane [`\textrm{A}`]'s trajectory is a straight line with [`\theta = 45^\circ`], while your trajectory in plane [`\textrm{B}`] is a circle of distance [`d_1 = [$d]\ \textrm{km}`] from its
center as shown below. At this instant, [`d_2 =`] [`[$rAB]\ \textrm{km}`] and the planes are in the position shown in the image. If plane [`\textrm{B}`] has
a velocity [`\vec v_B=[$vB]\ \textrm{km/s}`] and a tangential acceleration [`(\vec a_B)_t=[$aB]\ \textrm{km/s}^2`] and plane [`\textrm{A}`] has a velocity
[`\vec v_A=[$vA]\ \textrm{km/s}`] and an acceleration [`\vec a_A=[$aA]\ \textrm{km/s}^2`] in the direction shown, find the velocity and acceleration of plane [`\textrm{A}`] as seen from
your window seat in plane [`\textrm{B}`].

[@ image( "22-R-KM-JL-08.png", width=>[$width], height=>[$height]) @]*


Determine the motion of plane [`\textrm{B}`]:

[`\vec{v}_B = `][_____]{"$vBi"}[`\hat{i}\ +`] [_____]{"$vBj"}[`\hat{j}\ km/s`]

[`\vec{a}_B = `][_____]{"$aBi"}[`\hat{i}\ +`] [_____]{"$aBj"}[`\hat{j}\ km/s^2`]


Determine the motion of plane [`\textrm{A}`]:

[`\vec{r}_{A/B} = `][_____]{"$rAB"}[`\hat{i}\ km`]

[`\vec{v}_A = `][_____]{"$vAi"}[`\hat{i}\ +`] [_____]{"$vAj"}[`\hat{j}\ km/s`]

[`\vec{a}_A = `][_____]{"$aAi"}[`\hat{i}\ +`] [_____]{"$aAj"}[`\hat{j}\ km/s^2`]


Find the information of the rotating frame:

[`\vec{\Omega} = `][_____]{"$omega"} [`\hat{k}\ rad/s`]

[`\dot{\vec{\Omega}} = `][_____]{"$omegaDot"} [`\hat{k}\ rad/s^2`]


Use the velocity equation with rotating axes to find [`\vec{v}_{A/B}`]:

[`\vec v_{A/B} = `][_____]{"$vABi"}[`\hat{i}\ +`] [_____]{"$vABj"}[`\hat{j}\ km/s`]


Use the acceleration equation with rotating axes to find [`\vec{a}_{A/B}`]:

[`\vec a_{A/B} = `][_____]{"$aABi"}[`\hat{i}\ +`] [_____]{"$aABj"}[`\hat{j}\ km/s^2`]


END_PGML

BEGIN_PGML_HINT
The acceleration of each plane [`\textrm{B}`] can be broken into it's tangential and normal components. Remember that the formula for the normal component [`\omega^2\cdot r`] can be re-written using [`v=\omega\cdot r`].
END_PGML_HINT

BEGIN_PGML_HINT
The velocity equation with rotating axes is: [`\vec{v}_A = \vec{v}_B+\vec{\Omega}\times\vec{r}_{A/B}+\vec{v}_{A/B}`] where [`\vec{v}_{A/B}`] is the 
velocity of [`\textrm{A}`] with respect to [`\textrm{B}`] (the velocity of [`\textrm{A}`] from [`\textrm{B}`]'s perspective).
END_PGML_HINT

BEGIN_PGML_HINT
The acceleration equation with rotating axes is: [`\vec{a}_A = \vec{a}_B+\dot{\vec{\Omega}}\times\vec{r}_{A/B}+\vec{\Omega}\times(\vec{\Omega}\times\vec{r}_{A/B})+2\cdot\vec{\Omega}\times\vec{v}_{A/B}+\vec{a}_{A/B}`] where [`\vec{a}_{A/B}`] is the 
acceleration of [`\textrm{A}`] with respect to [`\textrm{B}`] (the acceleration of [`\textrm{A}`] from [`\textrm{B}`]'s perspective).
END_PGML_HINT

